#- §l§oChapter 5:§0
§0§l§oSecret Room/Passage on Same Level§0
§0   The variation here is in the location of the piston door. In order to hide an entrance, you will need to find or make a corner or a “one-off” column of blocks against a
#- wall – basically, a place in which the door looks like part of the wall until retracted, and yet also where (once the door is retracted) there can be a concealed passage or room. An example illustrated...
#- §oDiagram 9:§0
§0(B = Block; P = Sticky Piston; # = Passage; - = Piston Extension; W = Wall)§0
§0
§0View from above:§0
§0
§0           #§0
§0       WWW#§0
§0           B-P§0...§0
§0           W§0
§0           W
#- §l§oChapter 6:§0
§0§l§oSecret Room/Passage on Lower Level§0
§0   The variation here, as in the last chapter, is in the location of the piston door. However, since the passage or room being concealed is below the level of the entryway, this is much easier
#- to hide, because the passageway itself doesn’t need to be concealed. In other words, the door itself simply needs to be concealed in a wall. However, it must be down, because if it the passage or room is up, there will be no way to climb. An example...
#- §oDiagram 10:§0
§0(B = Block; P = Sticky Piston; # = Passage; - = Piston Extension; W = Wall)§0
§0
